<li>Nextdoor</li>
<li>PetGroomer.com</li>
<li>DogGrooming.com</li>
<li>Better Business Bureau</li>
<li>Local Chamber of Commerce</li>
</ul>
<p>Consistency matters more than quantity. Your business name, address, and phone number must be identical across every listing. One digit off in your phone number can confuse Google and hurt your rankings.</p>
<h3>Local Backlinks</h3>
<p>Backlinks from local websites carry more weight than generic directory links. Target these sources:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Local pet blogs and publications.</strong> Offer to write a guest post about grooming tips.</li>
<li><strong>Veterinarian websites.</strong> Many vets will list recommended groomers on their website.</li>
<li><strong>Pet supply stores.</strong> Cross-promote with local pet shops.</li>
<li><strong>Local business associations.</strong> Join your city's small business network.</li>
<li><strong>Pet rescue organizations.</strong> Sponsor adoption events and get listed on their site.</li>
<li><strong>Local news and community sites.</strong> Offer grooming tips for seasonal stories.</li>
</ul>
<p>Each local backlink signals to Google that your grooming business is trusted in your community. That trust translates directly into higher local pack rankings.</p>
